properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for the Buffalo River.

MINOR TO MODERATE FLOODING MAY DEVELOP FROM OVERNIGHT WEDNESDAY INTO THURSDAY   

A cold front will move eastwards across Victoria today, bringing areas of heavy rainfall and thunderstorms to the northern part of the state.   

Widespread rainfall totals of 10 mm with isolated up to 25 mm have been observed in the flood watch area in the 24 hours to 9 AM today.   

Catchments across central and northeastern Victoria are average to wet, and catchments across the northwest are relatively dry.   

Widespread rainfall totals of 40 to 60 mm are expected in the flood watch area from Wednesday afternoon into Thursday, with isolated heavier falls of 60 to 80 mm possible with thunderstorms and about higher terrain. Isolated totals in excess of 120 mm are possible over the higher peaks in the northeast. Showers and thunderstorms are forecast to ease from the west during Thursday.   

River level rises are likely in catchments within the flood watch area, where minor flooding may develop from overnight Wednesday into Thursday. Moderate flooding is also possible in areas with the heaviest rainfall.   

A Severe Weather Warning for heavy rainfall is current for parts of Victoria.

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 08/06/2023 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Ovens river to Bright and Rocky Point.

MINOR TO MODERATE FLOODING LIKELY OVERNIGHT WEDNESDAY

Rainfall totals of 5-15 mm have been observed since 9am Wednesday due to heavy showers and thunderstorms ahead of a cold pressure system. The higher of these totals fell over the Fifteen Mile Creek and upper King River.

River levels are expected to rise above the minor level overnight Wednesday to Thursday morning for several forecast sites. The King River at Docker Rd Bridge is forecast to reach the moderate flood level early Thursday.

Further rainfall totals of 40-60 mm is forecast across the Ovens and King Rivers and tributaries, with higher rainfall totals of 60-80 mm expected in the upper parts of the catchment, with isolated totals exceeding 120mm possible. The forecast rain is likely to produce further river level rises.

Ovens River to Bright:
Minor flooding may occur along the Ovens River to Bright. The Ovens River at Bright is currently at 1.35 metres and steady, below the minor flood level. The Ovens River at Bright may reach the minor flood level (3.00 m) Thursday morning. Further rises possible with forecast rain. 

Ovens River Bright to Rocky Point:
Minor flooding is likely along the Ovens River Bright to Rocky Point. The Ovens River at Eurobin is currently at 2.32 metres and steady, below the minor flood level. The Ovens River at Eurobin may reach the minor flood level (4.50 m) Thursday afternoon. Further rises possible with forecast rain.The Ovens River at Rocky Point is currently at 1.39 metres and steady, below the minor flood level. The Ovens River at Rocky Point is likely to reach the minor flood level (3.20 m) Thursday afternoon. Further rises possible with forecast rain.

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 08/06/2023 10:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au

This is a Threat is Reduced Advice Message for Halls Gap.
  • The immediate threat of flash flooding has passed. 
  • Dangerous hazards including floodwater, mud, debris, damaged roads, and fallen trees may still be present.
  • This Advice message replaces the Watch and Act issued at 1228.
The threat of flooding is reduced. You can now return to normal activity, but be aware of any hazards that may still exist in the warning area.
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is dangerous - do not enter floodwater. 
  • Find alternative travel routes if roads or underpasses are flooded. 
  • Be aware of driving hazards, such as mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees. 

If your home or business has been flooded: 
  • Check for building damage before you enter. 
  • Have all electrical and gas equipment professionally tested before use. 
  • Clean and dry out the building as soon as possible. 

Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For emergency assistance from the SES call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Several local roads have been affected by recent flash flooding.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

This will be the last warning issued for this flood. 

Flood information: 
  • Further flash flood information for some areas can be found in Local Flood Guides. 
  • For river heights check the Bureau of Meteorology website or phone 1300 659 217. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Prepare for flooding now. Take actions to protect your life and property against potential hazards caused by flooding.
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Rising floodwater can be dangerous. Be aware of water levels rising near you.
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.

ADVICE - RIVERINE FLOOD - Stay Informed
Incident Location: the Goulburn River Eildon to Seymour
Issue Date: Wednesday 07 June 2023, 02:21 pm
Next Update: Thursday 08 June 2023, 03:00 pm

More details at http://emergency.vic.gov.au/respond/#!/warning/29400/moreinfo

This Flood Watch is being issued for the Goulburn River Eildon to Seymour.

MINOR TO MODERATE FLOODING MAY DEVELOP FROM OVERNIGHT WEDNESDAY INTO  THURSDAY    

A cold front will move eastwards across Victoria today, bringing areas of heavy rainfall and thunderstorms to the northern part of the state.    

Widespread rainfall totals of 10 mm with isolated up to 25 mm have been observed in the flood watch area in the 24 hours to 9 AM today.    

Catchments across central and northeastern Victoria are average to wet, and catchments across the  northwest are relatively dry.    

Widespread rainfall totals of 40 to 60 mm are expected in the flood watch area from Wednesday afternoon into Thursday, with isolated heavier falls of 60 to 80 mm possible with thunderstorms and about higher terrain. Isolated totals in excess of 120 mm are possible over the higher peaks in the northeast. Showers and thunderstorms are forecast to ease from the west during Thursday.    

River level rises are likely in catchments within the flood watch area, where minor flooding may develop from overnight Wednesday into Thursday. Moderate flooding is also possible in areas with the heaviest rainfall.    

A Severe Weather Warning for heavy rainfall is current for parts of Victoria.    

Catchments likely to be affected include:    
- Upper Murray and Mitta Mitta Rivers 
- Kiewa River 
- Ovens and King Rivers 
- Seven and Castle Creeks 
- Goulburn River Eildon to Seymour 




Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point.

MINOR TO MODERATE FLOODING LIKELY OVERNIGHT WEDNESDAY 

Rainfall totals of 5-15 mm have been observed since 9am Wednesday due to heavy showers and thunderstorms ahead of a cold pressure system. The higher of these totals fell over the Fifteen Mile Creek and upper King River.

River levels are expected to rise above the minor level overnight Wednesday to Thursday morning for several forecast sites. The King River at Docker Rd Bridge is forecast to reach the moderate flood level early Thursday.

Further rainfall totals of 40-60 mm is forecast across the Ovens and King Rivers and tributaries, with higher rainfall totals of 60-80 mm expected in the upper parts of the catchment, with isolated totals exceeding 120mm possible. The forecast rain is likely to produce further river level rises.

Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point:

Minor flooding may occur along the Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point.

The Ovens River at Wangaratta is currently at 9.08 metres and rising, below the minor flood level. The Ovens River at Wangaratta may exceed the minor flood level (11.90 m) Thursday afternoon. Further rises are possible with forecast rain.


Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 08/06/2023 10:50 am or as the situation changes.
